    "Sottotitolo": "tracce",
    "Titolo": "Epitaph of Santa Monica",
    "Image": "Immagini/tracce/traccia_32.png",
    "Descrizione": "<p>This fragmentary epitaph from Ostia commemorates the death of St. Monica (c. 322 – 387 CE), mother of St. Augustine, Church Father and Bishop of Hippo (354 – 430 CE), whose pious influence was instrumental in his conversion to Christianity. It demonstrates how individuals travelled and mixed through the late Roman empire and how the memory of women was often associated with that of men, while at the same time representing a puzzle to modern scholars as the epitaph was inscribed decades if not centuries after her burial and thus demonstrates the sometimes complex relationship between language, writing, memory, and material objects.<br>Monica, whose name is of Berber origin, may have spoken either a Berber language or Punic, the language St. Augustine associates with the Numidian countryside, in addition to the Latin used in the administrative centres and by her Roman husband. (St. Augustine himself knew enough Punic to help him translate from the Hebrew). Their linguistic situation is typical of the Roman Empire where many peoples and languages coexisted and there was much movement across linguistic and cultural borders.</p>",
    "Descrizione2": "<p class='small_text'>In his autobiographical <i>Confessions</i>, St. Augustine narrates his mother’s passing in Ostia in 387 CE. Having recently been baptised in Milan by its bishop, St. Ambrose, St. Augustine began his journey home to Thagaste, Numidia, in the company of his son, mother and brother. Monica died in transit. Some days before her death, St. Augustine attributes the following words to Monica: 'Put this body anywhere. Do not let care about it disturb you. I ask only this: that you remember me at the altar of the Lord, wherever you may be' (9.11.27), which explains why she was buried in Ostia and not transported back to her home in North Africa. <br>The stone epitaph, which names St. Augustine but not Monica, post-dates her death. Since in 387 CE, St. Augustine had yet to serve the church in the important ways he would later on, the epitaph was probably written after St. Augustine’s death but before the cult of Santa Monica had gained prominence.  Although the tombstone fragment (with parts of the terracotta tomb) was unearthed only in 1945 in a small courtyard next to the church of St. Aurea (patron saint of Ostia, martyred in the 3rd century CE), the complete epitaph in post-classical Latin elegiac couplets was well-known from medieval manuscripts. The earliest is the <i>7th century Sylloge Turonensis</i>, a compendium of epitaphs and inscriptions which received numerous later editions often appended to the popular <i>Etymologies</i> of Isidore of Seville. In three 11th century copies (Codex Parisinus Lat. 8093, Parisinus Lat. 8094 and Vossianus q. 69) the epitaph is attributed to an ‘ex-consul Bassus’, possibly Ancius Auchenius Bassus (consul in 408 CE), but it could have been another member of this noted Roman family, or the attribution may be spurious.  <br>Further complications arise when considering the circumstances of the epitaph’s composition: was it meant to be carved on her tombstone or was it first written as a textual commemoration of her and only later copied from manuscript to tombstone? The fact that the text does not name Monica or her age at the time of death or death date suggests that the poem was written as a literary commemoration that was later transferred to stone. The style of the lettering is similar to that of another shorter epitaph for Bishop Cyriacus (martyred in 269 CE), whose remains may have been re-commemorated at the same time, probably around the 6th century. <br>In 1430, Pope Martin V had St. Monica’s relics brought to Rome and they now reside in an elegant tomb and dedicated chapel in the church of St. Agostino.</p>",
    "Dati_box": "<p class='small_text'><b>Location:</b> Ostia Antica, Basilica of Saint Aurea, left wall inside the church <br><b>Date: </b>post-387 CE<br><b>Materials: </b>Marble, severely damaged and broken, with portions missing. Full inscription known only from early manuscript sources <br><b>Language: </b>Latin<br><b>Writing systems and Scripts: </b>Latin alphabet, majuscule<br><b>Traslation: </b><br>Stone Fragment of Tomb Inscription: HIC POSVIT CINE…AVGVSTINE TV…QVI SERVANS PA…COMMISSOS PO…GLORIA VOS M…VIRTVTVM…M<br><br>Epitaph from manuscript sources attrib. to ‘Bassus’ <br>Hic posuit cineres genetrix castissima prolis, <br> Augustine tui altera lux meriti, <br>Qui servans pacis caelestia iura sacerdos<br> Commissos populos moribus instituis. <br>Gloria vos maior gestorum laude coronat<br>   Virtutum mater felicior subolis. <br>Here Augustine, another light of your merits, placed the ashes of his most virtuous mother. You taught the people as a priest, with your character and maintaining the heavenly laws of peace. Glory greater than your deeds crowns you (both), the mother more fortunate because of the virtues of her offspring.</p>",
    "Bibliografia": "<p class='small_text'><b>Bibliography</b><br>Augustine, Saint, Bishop of Hippo, Confessions. With an English Translation by William Watts. Loeb Classical Series (London, 1912) <br>Boin, Douglas Ryan, ‘Late Antique Ostia and a Campaign for Pious Tourism: Epitaphs for Bishop Cyriacus and Monica, Mother of Augustine’, The Journal of Roman Studies, 100 (2010), 195-209 <br>Brown, Peter, Augustine of Hippo: A Biography. New Edition with an Epilogue  (Berkeley, 2000) <br>Bücheler, Francis and Alexander Riese, Anthologia latina sive poesis latinae supplementum, part I, section 2 (Leipzig, 1894-1926), no. 670  <br>Casamassa, A., ‘Ritrovamento di parte dell’elogio di S. Monica’, Rendiconti. Pontificia Accademia Romana di Archeologia, 27 (1952-4), 271-73  <br>Holgate, Ian, ‘The Cult of Sant Monica in Quattrocento Italy: Her Place in Augustinian Iconography, Devotion and Legend’, Papers of the British School at Rome, 71 (2003), 181-206 <br>De Rossi, Giovanni Battista, Inscriptiones christianae urbis Romae septimo saeculo antiquiores, II/1 (Rome, 1857-88), no. 252  <br>Meiggs, Russell, Roman Ostia (Oxford, 1960). <br>van den Hoek, Annewies, ‘Peter, Paul, and a Consul: Recent Discoveries in African Red Slip Ware’, Zeitschrift für Antikes Christentum, 9 (2006), 197-246 <br>Wischmeyer, Wolfgang, ‘Zum Epitaph der Monica’, Römische Quartalschrift, 70 (1975), 32-41</p>",
    "Crediti": "<p class='small_text'><b>Credits</b><br><b>Image:</b> Public Domain<br><b>Transcription:</b> Anthologia Latina, sive poesis Latinae supplementum, no. 670.</p>",
    "Autore": "<p class='Autore_text'><i> Maia Wellington Gahtan</i></p>",
